article.description: After a one-year absence, Jerry Stackhouse is back as a primary scoring option.
article.headline: Stack drops 35 on Cavs; Jordan held to six points
article.linkText: Stackhouse takes control, steers Wizards to victory
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Jerry Stackhouse muttered a complaint or two after his first few games with the Washington Wizards -- he felt he wasn't getting to the free-throw line as often as usual.
Stackhouse

No such problems Wednesday night. Stackhouse scored 35 points, shooting 9-of-16 from the field and 15-of-17 from the line, and the Wizards never trailed as they broke a two-game losing skid with a 107-100 victory over the Cleveland Cavaliers. ''Sometimes a little whisper in the wind helps,'' said Stackhouse, who averaged about 7.5 free throws in Washington's first four games. On a night when Michael Jordan was a facilitator -- not even scoring until the fourth quarter -- Stackhouse scored eight straight points in a game-opening 19-3 run, and his hustle and energy helped rebuild the lead after the Cavaliers cut it to three at halftime. ''He sets the tone,'' said Jordan, who had six points and four assists in 24 minutes. ''My job, when I get in there, is to keep that momentum going. When he's in the game with me, obviously I'm going to do everything I can to keep him in that rhythm. Whenever he falters, hopefully I can be there to help pick him up. ''I'm just keeping things moving. That's what you see out there, the future of this franchise. Me, I'm just complementing whenever we need it,'' he said. Ricky Davis scored 27 points to lead the Cavaliers, who were coming off a home victory over the Los Angeles Lakers the night before. ''We looked like a team on the second night of a back-to-back,'' Cavaliers coach John Lucas said. ''I thought we did a great job to get back in the game. Then at the start of the third quarter, we fell back. They did a lot of good things defensively. They really challenged each shot and they hustled well.'' The Wizards were also playing back-to-back games after losing at Minnesota on Tuesday. ''This was a great win, and we needed it,'' said coach Doug Collins, who is determined to avoid a repeat of last year's 2-9 start. Stackhouse led the Wizards to the early lead as the out-of-sync Cavaliers missed seven of their first eight shots and had four offensive fouls in the first quarter. Stackhouse alone outscored Cleveland 17-13 in the quarter and shot 6-of-7, including an alley-oop dunk and a 3-pointer that helped push the lead to 17 points. The Cavaliers started pressing full-court in the second quarter, and an overall more intense defense paid off as they cut into the lead. Jumaine Jones' block turned into a layup for Davis, and Davis picked Jordan from behind and was rewarded with a breakaway layup at the other end. A 10-2 run closed it to 46-43 at the half. The Cavaliers never got any closer as Stackhouse reasserted himself in the second half. He made a behind-the-back pass to Brendan Haywood for a layup and a fast-break pass to Larry Hughes while lying flat on his back following a steal. Up 73-66 after three, the Wizards opened the fourth with an 8-0 run to put the game away. ''I had to come out and be aggressive,'' Stackhouse said. ''That opens a lot of things for everybody. I'm finding ways as I get more comfortable with the offense, how to pick my spots, when to go.'' Game notes
Washington took 43 free throws to Cleveland's 22. ... Hughes popped Cleveland's Bimbo Coles in the face while driving to the basket in the second quarter. Hughes was called for an offensive foul, while Coles was out of the game for a few minutes with a bruised jaw. ... Cleveland center Zydrunas Ilgauskas started 1-for-12, not an easy feat considering he rarely strays far from the basket. ... Someone other than Coles finally made a 3-pointer for Cleveland. The Cavaliers were 3-for-13 -- with Coles 3-for-7 -- from long range entering the game. Darius Miles hit one in the third quarter, and Smush Parker had one in the fourth. ... Hughes had a jump shot at the third-quarter buzzer overruled after a video replay review.
